{{Infobox artwork | image_file=Paul_Gauguin_121.jpg | image_size=300px | title=Still Life with Head-Shaped Vase and Japanese Woodcut | artist=Paul Gauguin | year={{Start date|1889}} | medium=Oil on canvas | height_imperial=28.5 | width_imperial=36.5 | imperial_unit= in | museum=[[Tehran Museum of Contemporary Art]] | city = [[Tehran]]}} '''''Still Life with Head-Shaped Vase and Japanese Woodcut''''' is an 1889 [[still life]] painting by French artist, [[Paul Gauguin]]. It is currently in the collection of the [[Tehran Museum of Contemporary Art|Museum of Contemporary Art]] in [[Tehran]], [[Iran]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://xroads.virginia.edu/~museum/armory/galleryR/gauguin.176.html | title=Paul Gauguin | accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>
== History == In 1888 and 1889 [[Paul Gauguin|Gauguin's]] enthusiasm for Japanese [[ukiyo-e]] [[woodcut]]s emerged. Japanese prints appeared in the background of his ''Apple and Vase'' painting, his portrait of ''The [[Émile Schuffenecker|Schuffenecker]] Family'' and also ''Still Life with Head-Shaped Vase and Japanese Woodcut'', which depicts an ukiyo-e portrait of an actor.{{sfn | Ives | 1980 | p=96}}
The painting was formerly owned by [[Josef Rosensaft]], a [[Holocaust]] survivor who led the community of Jewish displaced persons, who died in September 1975. He left a formidable art collection that had to be sold to settle debts related to the acquisition of the art and by some accounts an extravagant lifestyle. The 1976 sale arranged by Sotheby’s was bought in its entirety by the [[Tehran Museum of Contemporary Art]], where it all remains today and is one of the oldest paintings in the museum's collection.<ref name="Bloomberg">[https://www.bloomberg.com/features/2015-tehran-museum-of-contemporary-art/ "Iran Has Been Hiding One of the World’s Great Collections of Modern Art"]. ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]''. Retrieved December 13, 2015.</ref> This sale set a record for '''Still Life with Japanese Woodcut''' at $1.4 million, and the work is currently valued at $45 million.<ref name="Bloomberg" />
During the direction of [[Mahmoud Shalouithe]], the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] and the [[Tate Modern]] in [[London]] tried to borrow the painting but the requests were rejected.{{sfn | موسوی | 2014}}
